description:
Tucked away in the mellow neighborhood of Cole Valley, Zazie is one of the most charming brunch destinations in the city. The vibe here is unmistakably Parisian with the brick interior and classic French posters. When you arrive, say a little prayer for an open table at their gorgeous back patio. Even if it's a little chilly outside, there are a bunch of heated lamps there to keep you nice and toasty.

Although the prices on the menu might seem daunting at first, keep in mind that tip is already included. Also, they are pretty serious about the whole no substitutions thing. We tried ordering Sarah Jane's Griddle Flight, substituting in the Miracle Pancake and the French Toast Tahiti, but they wouldn't allow it. There was no stopping us from ordering each one separately though, so we ended up creating our own flight anyway.

// Miracle Pancakes ($9 / 1 piece) - 5 stars
Incredibly light and fluffy! I found that the maple syrup was unnecessary since the pancake came with a generous dollop of lemon curd.

// French Toast Tahiti ($9 / 1 piece) - 4 stars
Order this if you enjoy banana desserts. There is a layer of mushed bananas and walnuts in between the two pieces of toast.

// Gingerbread Pancakes ($9 / 1 piece) - 5 stars
The gingerbread flavor was quite predominant. This pancake had an almost cake-like consistency. It is certainly thicker and more dense than the Miracle Pancake.

// Eggs Benedict St. Trop ($21 / 2 eggs) - 4 stars
The creaminess of the hollandaise and the tartness of the capers really shined through. However, I wish there were more salmon and less red onions. The side of home fries came with delicious roasted garlic cloves.

Intimate brunch spot, but be prepared to wait! 

// SERVICE // Pleasant and quick considering the long waits outside 

// FOOD // 
     + Croque Madame: soft melted cheese and crunchy bread. A great glutinous warm sandwich for a crisp SF day. 

* tip: come at opening to avoid a long wait!
